fse

We fitted a linear mixed model (estimated using REML and nloptwrap optimizer) to predict fse with age, group and time_point (formula: fse ~ 1 + age + group + time_point + group * time_point). The model included login_id as random effect (formula: ~1 | login_id). The models total explanatory power is substantial (conditional R2 = 0.77) and the part related to the fixed effects alone (marginal R2) is of 0.18. The models intercept, corresponding to age = 0, group = control and time_point = 1st , is at 14.74 (S.E. = 2.78, p < .001, 95% CI [9.30, 20.19]). Within this model:

  • The effect of age is statistically non-significant and positive (beta = 0.07, S.E. = 0.05, p = 0.117, 95% CI [-0.02, 0.16]; Std. beta = 0.29, 95% CI [-0.07, 0.65])
  • The effect of group [treatment] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -0.87, S.E. = 1.38, p = 0.528, 95% CI [-3.57, 1.83]; Std. beta = -0.24, 95% CI [-1.00, 0.51])
  • The effect of time point [2nd] is statistically non-significant and positive (beta = 0.24, S.E. = 0.80, p = 0.759, 95% CI [-1.31, 1.80]; Std. beta = 0.07, 95% CI [-0.37, 0.50])
  • The interaction effect of time point [2nd] on group [treatment] is statistically significant and positive (beta = 3.34, S.E. = 1.12, p = 0.003, 95% CI [1.14, 5.54]; Std. beta = 0.94, 95% CI [0.32, 1.55])

Standardized parameters were obtained by fitting the model on a standardized version of the dataset. 95% Confidence Intervals (CIs) and p-values were computed using a Wald normal distribution approximation.
